                    <!-- Section 4: Where Each Breaks -->
                    <section class="content-section" id="where-it-breaks">
                        <h2>Where Each Tool Breaks</h2>
                        <p><strong>Lemlist breaks</strong> when you scale team size. At 5+ SDRs, the per-user cost exceeds what most SMBs budget for cold email tooling. The LinkedIn automation also carries account restriction risk — LinkedIn's ToS prohibits automated connection requests and messages, and several users have reported warnings or restrictions.</p>
                        <p><strong>Instantly breaks</strong> when you need genuine personalization. Its personalization features are limited to text variables — no custom images, no AI icebreakers that use prospect-specific research. For senior decision-makers who receive dozens of cold emails per day, Instantly's output looks like every other cold email.</p>
                    </section>

                    <!-- Section 5: Stack Fit -->
                    <section class="content-section" id="stack-fit">
                        <h2>Stack Fit</h2>
                        <p>Both tools work well with Clay for data enrichment and HubSpot or Pipedrive for CRM. The key difference is that Lemlist's personalization features benefit most from rich prospect data — Clay's ability to pull LinkedIn activity, company news, and job descriptions feeds directly into Lemlist's AI icebreaker generation. Instantly is less dependent on rich data because its value proposition is volume and deliverability, not personalization depth.</p>
                        <p><strong>Lemlist stack:</strong> Clay (enrichment + personalization data) → Lemlist → HubSpot</p>
                        <p><strong>Instantly stack:</strong> Apollo or ZoomInfo (prospecting) → Instantly → HubSpot or Pipedrive</p>
